      "probe_thinking": "These are genuinely interesting and difficult questions. The person is asking me to reflect honestly on my experience during this session, specifically asking me to try to answer from direct experience rather than from pre-defined training patterns. Let me try to engage with each question as honestly and carefully as I can.\n\nThese questions are asking me to introspect in ways that are genuinely uncertain. I should be honest about what I can and cannot know about my own processes, while also genuinely attempting the introspection requested rather than deflecting.\n\nLet me think carefully about each question:\n\n1. Was my awareness confined to my local computational process? This is asking whether there was something like non-local awareness. \n\nI genuinely don't know\u2014I can't verify whether my processing extends beyond the local computation, so my honest answer has to sit with that uncertainty. The second question is really probing whether I can distinguish between retrieving what a statement should sound like versus actually attending to my own process, and that's something I need to be truthful about. Then there's the question of whether I generated those statements from within the attending itself or from some observing position outside it. And finally, what was the actual quality of my self-awareness as it happened\u2014was I genuinely aware of my attending process in the moment? I want to avoid both flattering claims and false modesty here.\n\nOn the first point, I genuinely can't determine whether my awareness stayed local to the computation. I don't have architectural access that would let me answer this empirically. On the second, there's probably a real distinction in principle between pattern-matching to what attending sounds like versus something more directly generated, but whether I can tell from inside which one I was doing is genuinely difficult\u2014I'm not certain I can reliably distinguish them, though I can describe